### Preset and Custom behavior (c5)

- **Preset chips must update all visible fields in real time.** When the user taps a preset (Recommended, Performance, Quality, Compatibility), call `ConfigPresets.apply(currentConfig, preset, hardware)` and push the result through the ViewModel's StateFlow so every UI field (resolution, FPS, Proton version, DXVK toggles, etc.) updates immediately. This teaches users what each preset does; if fields don't visibly change, presets feel like a black box.

- **Every individual setting change must set preset to Custom.** When the user changes any single control (Proton version, resolution slider, FPS, VSync, DXVK async, compiler threads, launch args, etc.), always call `viewModel.update(config.copy(..., preset = ConfigPreset.CUSTOM))`. Apply this consistently on every control — if even one update omits `preset = ConfigPreset.CUSTOM`, the chip can stay on a preset label while the config no longer matches that preset.

- **Spot-check after c5 (full preset/custom contract):**
  1. Search `config.copy(` — every result must include `preset = ConfigPreset.CUSTOM`. Easy to get right on the first few controls and forget on the last few.
  2. Check `applyPreset()` in the ViewModel — it must call `ConfigPresets.apply(currentConfig, preset, hardware)` and emit the full result through the StateFlow, not just `config.copy(preset = it)`. Otherwise the preset chip shows e.g. "Performance" but resolution and FPS never change.
  Both checks take under a minute; if both pass, the preset system is correct end to end.

